Date:  0/0/1876
Source:  TrNZi
Author:
Vol / Page:  9/148
Edition:
Quote:  Kamai is called black birch in the Catlin River District and Southland, which name is given on account of a supposed resemblance to the `birches', or more correctly, `beeches', a number of which occur in that locality. i cannot understand how such an idea could have originated, for except in the ease of the bark of one there is not the slightest resemblance between the birches and kamai. Whatever be the reason, the misapplication of names is complete, for the birches are still commonly called kamai in Southland.
Notes:  Blair

