Vol / Page:  197
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Tawhero & W. sylvicola; Kamahi W. racemosa</i>. Kamahi ... is particularly common in the forests of Westland where it is usually termed red birch (!), but most of the popular names there are misnomers. The foliage of the kamahi is much used particularly in Christchurch for decorative purposes, and sold under the name `red birch'.
